  "analysis": "C++ rejects `#!` as an invalid preprocessing directive. Rust accepts `#![allow(unused)] /*` and then a block comment. So `#!` won't work for C++. We need the first line to be valid/harmless in C++. Let me test using a normal comment line `//` followed by something, and also test if C++ accepts a line starting with `#` followed by a number or `#pragma`. Another idea: use `#if 0` for C++ to skip a `/*`, and for Rust, put the `/*` on the same line before `#if 0` but hide the `/*` from C++ via a string or comment. Let me test: `/*#if 0` — Rust sees block comment start; C++ sees `/*` starting a block comment, not `#if`. Not good. What about `///*` for Rust? Rust sees `//` line comment, not block. Need block for Rust. Let me test using `r#\"\"#` raw string in Rust attribute and C++ sees it as preprocessor? No. Let me search for polyglot patterns online? No internet. Let me test a known trick: `#define X /*` for C++ and Rust sees it as attribute? No. Let me test if Rust accepts `#` followed by `!` only in inner attributes. We need C++ to ignore the first line. What if first line is `#if 0` and Rust is told to ignore it via `#![cfg_attr(...)]`? No. Let me test a different approach: use `fn main(){}` first for Rust, and hide C++ main behind `#[cfg(any())]` module. For C++, hide Rust `fn main` with a block comment started by a macro. Let me test C++ with `#define RUST_MAIN_START /*` then Rust code then `*/`. C++ would skip Rust code. Then Rust must ignore the `#define` and `*/`. If we put `#define RUST_MAIN_START /*` inside a Rust block comment, Rust ignores it. But we're back to same problem. Let me test a concrete pattern: line1 `/*` for Rust and C++ both see comment; but C++ needs `#define` visible. What if line1 is `/*/` for Rust (starts block comment) and C++ sees `/*/` as a block comment start containing a `/`? Both see comment. Hmm. What if we use C++ trigraphs or line splicing with backslash? In C++, a backslash at end of line continues the line. Rust does not continue lines with backslash. So we could make line1 end with backslash, causing C++ to join line1 and line2, while Rust treats them separately. Let me test: line1 `//` then line2 `#define ...`? Rust sees `//` comment on line1, then line2 `#define` as code -> fails. But if line1 is `/*\\` then C++ joins line1 `/*` with line2, making `/*#define...` a comment. Not good. If line1 is something that starts Rust block comment and ends with backslash so C++ joins and the `/*` is hidden? For example line1 `/*\\` line2 `*/ #define X`? Rust sees `/*` block comment start, ignores line2 until a `*/`; C++ joins `/*` + `*/ #define X` -> `/*/ #define X` which is a block comment `/* / #define X */`? Let me test C++ line splicing and Rust behavior.",
  "plan": "Test C++ line splicing with backslash and Rust block comment behavior to find a way to hide a `/*` from C++ while Rust sees it.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "printf '%s\\n' '/*\\\\' '*/ #define X 1' 'int main(){return 0;}' > /tmp/t.cpp\ncat -A /tmp/t.cpp\ng++ -x c++ /tmp/t.cpp -o /tmp/tcpp 2>&1 | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "printf '%s\\n' '/*\\\\' '*/ fn main(){}' > /tmp/t.rs\ncat -A /tmp/t.rs\nrustc /tmp/t.rs -o /tmp/t 2>&1 | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}
